ἐννοίας. This term belongs in strictness to the Stoics, rather than to Plato and his school. The former, it is true, admitted innate ideas, but considered them not as expressions of the ἀνάμνησις, but as the result os sensible impressions.

58. Quumque nihil esset, &c. Nihil, nothing of that which we per- ceive by means of the senses ; esse (here, and twice in the paren- thesis) is equivalent to vere esse.
